are given here.

302
00:31:27,280 --> 00:31:32,710
See also the website given at the bottom for
a more detailed description.

303
00:31:32,710 --> 00:31:39,659
The width of the outermost ring, Delta r_N,
is equal to the square-root of the wavelength

304
00:31:39,659 --> 00:31:45,130
times the focal length/divided by large N,
the total number of rings.

305
00:31:45,130 --> 00:31:55,039
An FZP of diameter r_N = 100 microns, consisting
of 4000 rings will have an outer ring thickness

306
00:31:55,039 --> 00:31:58,799
of 50 nm.

307
00:31:58,799 --> 00:32:05,600
Such a delicate structure is synthesized by
electron-beam lithography.

308
00:32:05,600 --> 00:32:13,340
Note also that the ultimate resolution of
an FZP is determined by Delta r_N, the outer-ring

309
00:32:13,340 --> 00:32:20,299
thickness, and is equal to a value a little
more than this, by a factor of 1.22.

310
00:32:20,299 --> 00:32:26,590
FZPs are used when requiring the tightest
focus, and values in the range of a few tens

311
00:32:26,590 --> 00:32:32,580
of nm for hard x-rays has been recently achieved.

312
00:32:32,580 --> 00:32:39,030
Lastly, it should be note that the inverse
dependence of the focal length on lambda implies

313
00:32:39,030 --> 00:32:43,420
a linear dependence with photon energy.

314
00:32:43,420 --> 00:32:50,300
This is less severe than the square dependence
of CRLs with energy, which can make FZPs more

315
00:32:50,300 --> 00:32:56,590
attractive for use with unmonochromatized
XFEL radiation, which can have a substantial

316
00:32:56,590 --> 00:32:58,440
bandwidth.

317
00:32:58,440 --> 00:33:03,240
The efficiency of FZPs is in general only
moderate.

318
